  "local_port": 50146,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I create hotspot for windows 10?",
  "response": "Creating a hotspot in Windows 10 allows you to share your internet connection with other devices wirelessly. Here\u2019s how to set it up:\n\n### Method 1: Using Windows Settings\n\n1. **Open Settings**:\n   - Press `Windows + I` to open the Settings app.\n\n2. **Network & Internet**:\n   - Click on **\"Network & Internet\"**.\n\n3. **Mobile Hotspot**:\n   - On the left sidebar, select **\"Mobile hotspot\"**.\n\n4. **Configure Hotspot**:\n   - Toggle the switch to **\"On\"** under \"Share my Internet connection with other devices\".\n   - Choose the internet connection you want to share (usually, this is your Wi-Fi or Ethernet connection) from the drop-down menu.\n\n5. **Network Name & Password**:\n   - Below the toggle, you can see the network name and password for your hotspot. You can click on the **\"Edit\"** button to change the network name and password to your preference.\n\n6. **Connect Devices**:\n   - Once the hotspot is active, use the network name (SSID) and password you set to connect other devices.\n\n### Method 2: Using Command Prompt\n\nIf you prefer a more hands-on approach or need more features, you can set up a hotspot using Command Prompt.\n\n1. **Open Command Prompt as Administrator**:\n   - Press `Windows + X` and select **\"Command Prompt (Admin)\"** or **\"Windows PowerShell (Admin)\"**.\n\n2. **Configure the Hotspot**:\n   - Type the following command, replacing `<NetworkName>` and `<Password>` with your desired network name and password:\n\n     ```bash\n     netsh wlan set hostednetwork mode=allow ssid=<NetworkName> key=<Password>\n     ```\n\n3. **Start the Hotspot**:\n   - Type the following command to start the hotspot:\n\n     ```bash\n     netsh wlan start hostednetwork\n     ```\n\n4. **Share Your Internet Connection**:\n   - Open `Network Connections` by pressing `Windows + R`, typing `ncpa.cpl` and pressing Enter.\n   - Right-click on your active internet connection (e.g., Wi-Fi or Ethernet) and select **\"Properties\"**.\n   - Go to the **\"Sharing\"** tab.\n   - Check the box that says **\"Allow other network users to connect through this computer's Internet connection.\"** Select the hosted network connection from the drop-down list below (usually named something like \"Local Area Connection* xx\").\n   - Click **\"OK\"** to apply the settings.\n\n5. **Connect Devices**:\n   - You can now connect your other devices using the network name and password you configured earlier.\n\n### Stopping the Hotspot\n\nTo stop the hotspot (if you used Command Prompt), type the following command in the Command Prompt:\n\n```bash\nnetsh wlan stop hostednetwork\n```\n\n### Notes\n\n- **Compatibility**: Make sure your wireless adapter supports hosted networks. Most modern adapters do, but if you encounter any issues, check your adapter's compatibility.\n- **Limitations**: The number of devices that can connect to your hotspot may depend on your hardware and Windows version.\n- **Performance**: Sharing your connection may affect your internet speed depending on the number of connected devices and your original connection speed.\n\nWith these steps, you should be able to create a hotspot in Windows 10 successfully!",
